## 3. Technique-by-Technique Breakdown

- Serve: Delivers high spin and good speed, but requires practiced, soft hands to keep the ball double-bouncing on the opponent's side.

- Receive
    - Push/Stop: Requires very active, precise racket angles. Passive touches will pop high.
    - Flick: Excellent. The rubber easily grabs the ball and the catapult effect handles the speed generation.
    - Chiquita/Banana: Very good. While T05 might generate a heavier curve, T80 provides a faster, more direct Chiquita that is very difficult to counter.

- Loop/Drive
    - First Loop (3rd Ball): Consistent and confidence-inspiring. The medium-high arc forgives slight timing errors.
    - Continuous Looping: Superb flow. The energy transfer is smooth, allowing for rapid, relentless topspin rallies without exhausting the player.
    - Power Loop / Kill: Very strong, though players with extreme physical power might feel it lacks the absolute maximum ceiling of harder ESN rubbers or T05.

- Countering
    - Counter-Topspin: One of its best attributes. It feels incredibly stable and reliable in topspin-to-topspin exchanges.
    - Punch Counter / Active Block: Highly effective. The rubber bites just enough before shooting the ball back with pace.

- Blocking
    - Passive Block: Effortless and deep. The ball springs off the racket with minimal physical input.
    - Active Block: Lethal. A slight forward press turns an incoming loop into a fast, flat counter.

- Smash & Flat Hit: Better than T05, as the pimple geometry allows the ball to penetrate the sponge easier for flat impacts. Very reliable for putting away high balls.

- Defense
    - Chop: Usable, but not ideal. The high bounce makes it difficult to keep the ball low and short against powerful loops.
    - Lob: Excellent. The trampoline effect allows for deep, high-spinning lobs from far behind the table with ease.

